Access to concessional resources and insurance cover for pioneering investments offer fragile nations the best tools to jump-start their economies, the African Development Bank (AfDB) has said. “It is important that the state provides risk-mitigating insurance for companies to promote investments in these frontier markets,” AfDB’s Vice President, Regional Development, Integration and Business Delivery, Khaled Sherif, said during a seminar organised on Tuesday by Waseda University and ICRC on the sidelines of the 7th Tokyo International Conference on African Development (TICAD7). The seminar, on post-conflict humanitarian needs and challenges, was titled: “Building a Better World Through Business – Challenges in Humanitarian Assistance in Africa and the Role of Private Sector. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY Sherif joined Peter Maurer, President of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), Aiji Tanaka, President of Waseda University and Izumi Kobayashi, former Vice Chair, Japan Association of Corporate Executives, on the high-level panel. Political, socio-economic and climate changes have slowed growth in countries across the continent, and statistics show that two out of every three countries in fragile situations around the world are found in Africa. Yet paradoxically, Africa has six of the world’s fastest growing economies and the continent’s GDP is predicted to rise to 4.1 per cent in 2020. Adesina assumes duty at AfDB, promises to curb inequality How FG’s innovative hub is facilitating IDPs resettlement Move from youth empowerment to youth investments – AfDB tells African leaders